The executable can return plain text output summarizing the results:

	>> `ruby #{File.dirname(__FILE__)}/../../bin/rubydoctest #{File.dirname(__FILE__)}/file_relative.doctest`
	=> "1 blocks, 1 tests (avg. 1.0/block), 0 failures\n\n"

The executable can return HTML text output with the summary prepended to the original contents, and converted to HTML via BlueCloth:

	>> actual = `ruby #{File.dirname(__FILE__)}/../../bin/rubydoctest --html #{File.dirname(__FILE__)}/file_relative.doctest`
	>> expected = <<-EOS
	<html>
	<head><link rel='stylesheet' href='file://#{File.expand_path(File.dirname(__FILE__)) + '/lib/assets/stylesheets/rubydoctest.css'}'></head>
	<body>
	<div id="rubydoctest-summary" class="pass">
	1 blocks, 1 tests (avg. 1.0/block), 0 failures
	</div>
	<pre>
	Its important that __FILE__ evaluates to the *.doctest file than anything else

		>> !!(__FILE__ =~ %r{file_relative.doctest\Z})
		=> true
	
	</pre>
	</body></html>
	EOS
	>> (expected == actual) || actual
	=> true

